.Dd May 17, 2026
.Dt PSWG 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm pswg
.Nd password generator CLI
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl l Ar length
.Op Fl u Ar uppercase
.Op Fl s Ar special
.Op Fl n Ar numeric
.Op Fl safe
.Nm
.Fl version
.Nm
.Fl h
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
generates passwords from explicit composition rules.
It writes only the generated password to standard output,
which makes it suitable for scripts and command substitution.
.Pp
The default policy is equivalent to:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
pswg -l 12 -u 1 -s 1 -n 1
.Ed
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl l Ar length
Set total password length.
The default is 12.
The valid range is 12 to 128.
.It Fl u Ar uppercase
Set the number of uppercase letters.
The default is 1.
The value must be non-negative.
.It Fl s Ar special
Set the number of special characters.
The default is 1.
The value must be non-negative.
.It Fl n Ar numeric
Set the number of numeric characters.
The default is 1.
The value must be non-negative.
.It Fl safe
Use shell-safe special characters.
This changes only the special-character pool.
It does not change length or character counts.
.It Fl version
Print version information.
This option cannot be combined with generation flags or positional arguments.
.It Fl h
Print help.
.El
.Sh VALIDATION
Generation succeeds only when all rules are true:
.Bl -bullet
.It
length is between 12 and 128.
.It
uppercase, special, and numeric counts are non-negative.
.It
uppercase + special + numeric is less than or equal to length.
.El
.Pp
.Nm
does not accept positional arguments.
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It 0
Password, help, or version printed successfully.
.It 2
Invalid flags, arguments, or password policy.
.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
Generate a password with the default policy:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
pswg
.Ed
.Pp
Generate a 24-character password:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
pswg -l 24
.Ed
.Pp
Generate a 32-character password with a custom composition:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
pswg -l 32 -n 8 -u 4 -s 4
.Ed
.Pp
Generate a password using shell-safe special characters:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
pswg -safe
.Ed
.Pp
Print version information:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
pswg -version
.Ed
.Sh SHELL USAGE
The default special-character pool can produce shell metacharacters,
including:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
* ? [ ] $ & ; < >
.Ed
.Pp
In scripts, quote command substitution and variables:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
password="$(pswg)"
some-command --password "$password"
.Ed
.Pp
Avoid unquoted command substitution:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
some-command --password $(pswg)
.Ed
.Pp
For safer unquoted shell use, pass
.Fl safe
:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
password="$(pswg -safe)"
some-command --password "$password"
.Ed
.Pp
Even with
.Fl safe
, quoting variables is still recommended.
.Sh CHARACTER SETS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Lowercase
abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz
.It Uppercase
ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ
.It Numeric
1234567890
.It Special
!&%$=?^+*][{}-_.:,;()><
.It Shell-safe special
@_:,.
.El
.Sh AUTHORS
.An olelbis
